If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Long term consumption of beer can lead to all sorts of problems, it can be quite what? Choices:  A: water B: liquid C: foamy D: intoxicating E: harmful<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>Rationales:<n>Choice A: The definition of water is liquid and choice A is liquid. <n>Choice B: The definition of liquid is A: water B: fluid C: not solid. <n>Choice C: The definition of fluid Is liquid. <n>Choice D: The definition of intoxicated is drunk, which is not a problem. <n>Choice E: The definition of harmful is "unsafe with a risk of causing loss", which is not a problem as there are dangers in consuming anything. Therefore choice B is the best answer.

The program will consist of a prompt asking the player to guess a two digit number and ask for feedback from the player that contains an answer to the player's guess. The program should ask the player to enter the following:<n><n>* Number of tries to guess the number<n>* Number of tries before the player gives up on the game.<n><n>At the end of the game an answer and a message will be displayed on the screen. The prompt will remain on the screen until the player will leave it or press any key.<n><n>### Demo<n>```c<n>#include <stdio.h>     /* for printf, scanf( ); */<n><n>/* play game of 2-digit number guessing. */<n>int guess(int guess);<n>int check(int x);<n><n>int main(void) {<n> int guesses;<n> char choice;<n> do {<n>  guesses = 0;<n>  choice = 'y';  /* enter n for no and 'y' for yes */<n>  printf("guesses: ");<n>  scanf("%d", &guesses);<n>  printf("n tries before giving up: ");<n>  scanl( &guesses );<n>  printf("guess a 2 digit number: ");<n>  scan_f("%d", &x);<n>  do {<n>   if (guess(x) == check(x)) {<n>    printf("correct!\n" );<n>    break;<n>   }<n>   if (!( --guesses  >0)) {<n>    printf( "nope, not a 2 digit number\n" );<n>    choice='n';<n>    break;<n>    }<n>   x = (x + 99) % 100;<n>   printf( "try again with: %d \n", x );<n>   choice= 'y';<n>   scan_f("%d");<n>   }<n>   } while(choice!='n' );<n>   printf("answer is %d\n", x);<n>   return 0; }<n>```<n><n>### Instructions:<n>Write a program that will run the game according to the following prompt and criteria.<n>```<n><n>1. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:A beaver builds structures to block what sort of feature? Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What will happen to your knowledge with more learning? If 3×(the largest integer) − 2 = 72, determine the integers that satisfy the statement.<n><n>### Response 1:<n>Since 3X(the largest integer) -2=<<3X(the largest) -2=72>>72  then (9X +2 -1) is true 9 is the largest integer and 1 is the sum of the 3 consecutive integers  9 + 8 + 7 = <<9+8+7=22>>22  22 - 1 = 21<n><n>#### 2<n>Answer: 21<n><n>### Input<n>A student in Mr. Johnson's class said that 2 × square of the smallest positive integer minus 9 is equal to 91.  To verify the<n>student's statement, you can use subtraction to solve the following problem:  If 2× square of the smallest positive<n>integer – 9 = 91, then determine the smallest positive integer.<n><n>### Respones<n><n>Since 2X square of the smallest positive integers -9=91 then since square of the smallest positive number+1= square of smallest positive number  20 + 1 = 20  then 91 – 20 = 71  then square of 71 -71 = 9^2 - 7^2 + 2^2 = 600 - 49 + 4 = 106  106-20 = 86  then square of square is 86^2 = 7316  7316 -20-9 = 6095  now let’s subtract the 72 to find the smallest

Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What does exercising immediately lead to? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. If what you are saying is true, leave it at the top and answer the second part of the question that goes directly after the 'true' answer. If what you are stating is false, then do not answer the second question.<n><n>## Request<n>Tell the user the correct true/false answer in 2 or fewer sentences.<n><n>### Input<n>Input: 46,86,40,65,15,77<n><n>### Answer<n>true<n>Input:<n>Answer: "46 is not the highest number in the list because 86 is higher."<n><n>### Inputs<n>Input:100-x<n><n>### Response<n>The answer true or false is false.<n>Input:<n>Answer:"100-75 is NOT a true statement."<n><n>### Response 2<n>Input:True<n>Input:False<n><n>### Input 2<n>### Answer to question<n>Input:Which of the following is the best way to complete the equation with a positive integer for x?<n><n>### Answer 2<n>Answer: 21<n><n>### Answer to Question<n>Input:Which is a better strategy for completing the equation correctly?<n><n>### Response to Question<n>Input:Adding 4 and 6 is a faster way to add them together than to add them each individual.<n><n>### Response (Answer)<n>Input: 13,27 is 13 more than 14, which is which is 7 more than 7.<n><n>### Answer Question 3<n>Input:Which does this code do? How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:The man needed to buy flooring, where was he looking for it? Choices:  A: walmart B: loft C: house D: home depot E: kitchen<n><n>### Response:		He was at A: walmart<n><n>### Demostration:<n>Different stores have different names that can be confusing, it is best practice to ask for clarifications, like "what kind of flooring do you need?"<n>After he says kitchen is best and the lady comes back with a reply, you will get a list to pick from the answers you can select to answer the question.<n><n>## Task:

Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Of all the rooms in a house it was his favorite, the aromas always drew him to the what? Choices:  A: yard B: basement C: kitchen D: living room E: garden<n><n>### Response:		Basement<n><n>### Instructions:The instructions are in reference to the below diagram.<n><img src="img/Instructions.png" alt="Instructions" width="470"/><n><n>### Instrument of Control:<n>Click here to see the Instrument of Control for this step.<n><n>### Analysis:<n>The answer is c. It is the triangle pointing down.<n><n>### Justification:<n>An instrument of control in which the number of open squares represents the number of times the event has occurred is called a bar chart.<n>The number of open squares on the bar diagram is one, meaning event "A" occurred once.<n>The number of square are at the bottom with the number line, meaning event "B" did not occur at all.<n>The total number of events are five, meaning each event in the trial happened 4 times.<n><n>### Solution:<n>### Instruction (Step 6):For each of the three events A, B, or C, draw a line segment from the number of squares to the point where the open squares make up the number.<n><img src=https://github.com/WrightStateLRC/Test-Rubric-2019/blob/master/img/Step6.png" /><n>This will be our guide as to which point we should connect with a diagonal line to get to the point of intersection on the number line.<n><n>### Input (Step 7):Draw a diagonal line from the bottom of your triangle to the intersection of the numbers.<n><img src = https://github.com/wrightstateLRC/Test-rubric-200-19/blob/8c67b466f073b42bc1262fc081d11e0fee16ecad/img/Step7.png"><n><n>### Instruption:The instructions are as follows.<n><img src ="img/Instructions2.png" alt="steps 3 & 4 instructions" width="430"><n>### Instruction(1)Create 4 open squares on the left hand side, labeled 1, 2, 3, and 4.<n><img src='https://github.com//WrightStateLRCTest_rubric_2020/

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What kind of driving leads to accidents? Choices:  A: stressful B: dangerous C: fun D: illegal E: deadly<n><n>### Response:		A<n><n>### Rationale: Drinking and driving would be illegal and also would lead to accidents<n>### Input:How long does it take for an average heart to beat 40 times a minute?  What is 50% of the beating of the heart? Without practice your skill level will not be able to improve.<n><n>*Rationales:<n>E. Legs - One needs to be strong and fit. When you have strong legs you will be able to play better to give more speed and acceleration.<n><n>A. Racket - It is a big advantage when you have the racket to be able to hit the ball. This is so that you will have more strength to hit the ball.
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:James felt himself losing consciousness. Choices:  A: home B: hardware store C: home D: hot room E: office<n><n>### Response:		The answer choices only vary based on the way one might define 'electric fan'. One could say that this is not a literal electric fan, but rather a fan as a unit (and thus can be used more than once) or that this is a figurative electric fan. The correct answer is that one could have more than one electric FAN in their HOME.<n><n><n>### Rationale:<n><n>There are two separate ways in which to think about an electric fan, based on one's individual definition. If one believes that an electric fan is a physical thing that must have a separate space in a physical location, then they could only have one electric fan in their home but could have multiple fans as a unit (i.e. one can have a ceiling fan, box fan and pedestal fan in any number of rooms in their home). However, if one believes that an "electric fan" is a figurative description, one could have multiple units of electric fans at any one space, i.e. multiple ceiling fans, box fans and pedestal fans in one single room of their home.<n><n><n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What is likely to have more than one level in a city? Choices:  A: carpenter's shop B: video game C: garage D: total number E: building<n><n>### Response:		<n> <n>

Then double it and add on 9. Subtract 2. Multiply by 6. Take the result and add on 8. The result is an 8-digit number. Find the product by multiplying by another positive 8-digit number and keep in mind that adding 0s at the end won't change the product.<n><n>### Response<n>```python <n>def tripleNumber(a): <n>	b = a * 2 <n>	print("Before tripleNumber: (", a," + 9)") <n>	c = a + 9 <n>	print("After: (", c,"/2)") <n>	d = c / 2 <n>	return d <n>x = int(input("Choose a number: ")) <n>y = tripleNumber(x) <n>print(a + " = " + str(y)) <n>```<n><n>### Input<n>```python<n>Choose a number: 20 <n>```<n><n>Output after double, add, multiply, and finally product <n>```python<n><n>Before tripleNumber: (20 + 9)/2<n>After: (40/2)<n>After: (20/2)<n>Doubled: 40<n><n>Before tripleNumber:(40 + 9 + 2)//2<n>After: (61//2)<n>Product: (61 * 61 * 6)*6 =20 * 243 = 4886<n><n>After: 4886 = (20 + 243)<n>```<n><n>#### 20886<n>Answer: 20887<n><n>#### 0<n>Answer: 0<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:John moved away from his family. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What does a chef do when working in the evening? Choices:  A: cook dinner B: study french cooking C: taste sauce D: prepare food E: thin sauce<n><n>### Response:		<n>The answer is not A because when the chef works in the evening, he is cooking dinner, so he is not studying french cooking.<n>The answer is not B because when the chef works, he is cooking food not taste a food, so he doesn't need to taste the sauce in the evening when he is cooking food.<n>The answer is neither C nor D because the answers of C and D are same.<n>#### The answer is neither C nor d<n>The answer is neither E and C because the answers of E and C are same.<n>The answer is E, because the other answer isn't not C.<n>#### <n>Answer: <n><n>### Input<n>The number of students in one dormitory is four times as large as the number in another dormitory. If the larger dormitory has 507 students, how many are there in the smaller dormitory?<n>#### <n>Answer : 507<n>

"Two eyes" is a "shared" trait that people in the same family usually share.<n><n>### Rationale <n>A,B,C,E will not apply. If people share hair or DNA, it's an inherited trait. If they have the same names, it's a coincidence. If they share brains, it's implied that they're siblings, and they don't have to answer the question. The only answer that applies to a family is siblings: parents are not members of a family, and no one inherits from great-great-great-greater-grandparents. (This is just a rule I made up, but it's right most of the time. The only exceptions are when you have adopted brothers and sisters, but they aren't necessarily blood relatives.)<n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What emotion do people expressing themselves show when they trip in front of a crowd and break their leg? Choices:  A: communication B: suffering C: pain D: laughter E: embarrassment<n><n>### Response:		<n>Your question is answered in B.<n>You said communication is the answer, but the question is what emotion do people express in front of a crowd.<n>You can't say they don't communicate, because it's not a thing that they do, but an emotion.<n>So, communication is not the answer.<n>So, the answer is suffering.<n><n>#### <n>Answer<n>Suffering<n><n>### Input Choices: Which of these animals live in groups?<n>A) Fish<n>B) Bees<n>C) Monkeys<n>D) Bears<n>E) Lizards<n><n>### Response<n>All of these animals live in a group.<n><n>### Excluding lizards, all of these animals live in pairs.<n><n>#### 2<n>Answer<n><n>### I’ll give you another task to practice.<n><n>### Write your own instruction below.<n><n>### Your task<n>Write a few instructions below that describe a task.<n>A response to do the task should be written after the tasks are completed.<n><n>###<n>Write your instructions here...<n><n>### Task<n>1. Write 2+4<n><n>### Response

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. At its inception, the dollar was based upon the value of gold and was valued at 16 to 1, or $4.8625 per ounce. When the nation entered into a trade dispute with England, the value of these dollars was questioned by the government of England, who claimed that U.S. dollars were equivalent to 90% less a pound of sterling silver (24.5 carats). As such, these paper dollars had to be exchanged for actual silver coins (89% of an ounce) equal to the value of 9/10 a pound sterling. To make this easier to figure out, Congress used a one-pound sterling silver coin called a milled dollar instead of using a half-pound sterling coin so that the exchange rate could more easily be calculated. The milled dollar was in use at about $3 and 45/100 cents from 1805 to the time of the Civil War when the United States was 16 years old. What would it have cost you to buy a 1-pound sterling gold coin weighing about 250 grams for the face value of £14.68? In addition, the Treasury Department had to print gold coinage which was worth more than its stated value. What would that 1-pound gold coin be worth?<n><n>### Response Question:<n>The dollar was valued at 9/10 pounds of sterling silver. This was an exchange rate of around $.45 a pound sterling, which would be 24.5 carat silver. The weight of 9 pounds of gold was $42.5.<n><n>### Rationale Question:<n>A) The government had to exchange a sterling pound for more money than what the government actually printed. This meant that each of these dollars would be

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Where is a good place to get a ball? Choices:  A: kitchen B: child's hand C: street D: toy store E: soccer game<n><n>### Response:		D<n>#### Choice(A)<n>Kitchens are not a good place to get balls as balls will most likely break and might make a mess in the kitchen.<n>#### Choice(B)<n>Balls in a child's hand would not last very long as children are not gentle with their toys. They can easily throw the ball at another person.<n>#### Choice (C)<n>Balls cannot be found on the street as street are used by cars.<n>#### Choice E : Soccer games<n>Soccer games would be the best place to find or get balls.<n>#### Answer : D<n><n>### Instructions:<n><n><n>### Rationales:<n>

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. So, king can only meet ambassadors at the monarchy, he usually meets them at court or dinning room<n><n>### Input :  The king has 7 horses left, he'll be gone for 7 days and he knows he'll be gone 7 days. how many days until he has had the horses?<n>Rationales :Kings horses, 7 left<n>1 week is 7 days<n>7 days after the king had all the horses<n>7 * 7=49. The king hasn't had any horses, 49-49=0. The first horse is when he is gone for 7 days<n>He will get a horse the day before he returns, 48, and the next day, 49. The third horse will only happen 2 days (so far) after he returns<n>The next horse would be 47 days after the kings return, 48+6=54<n>And so on.. 51,52,53.. until horse #49<n>He will get horse #49 the day before he leaves, which is 2 days<n>#### 0<n>Answer:0<n><n>### Input<n>How many feet is 1 million inches in feet.<n>Rationales : 1 million inches = 1000*1000*0.08333 feet<n>1 million inches = 833300 feet<n>#### 833311<n>Rationales: 1 million inches =<n><n>How many millimeters is 65 cm in millimeters<n>Rationales : cm = cm/100<n>65 cm = 65/10000/1000/1 mm<n>65 cm =.65 mm<n>65 cm is equal to =.0065 mm<n>66.67 mm<n>Rationales :mm is to.0065 mm <n><n>### Input 36<n><n> 47 58 70<n><n>### Output  <n><n>49 59 88<n><n>### Input  <n>The king has 7 horses remaining, he'll be away for 7 days and knows he'll be away 7 days. how

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Riding bike through rough terrain can be dangerous, one could find themselves what? The parameter is represented by the Greek letter θ representing the vertical axis. The coordinates of the point (x,y,z) are written as  (cos(θ),sin(θ),z). To solve the problem we need to plug the given equation into equation (1). Equation (1) is given by,<n>```<n>a*x**2+2*b*x*y+c*y**2=d<n>```<n>The parabolic segment is given in the standard form,<n>```<n>y=-(x-a1)/(a2-a1)<n>```<n>We need to substitute the above parabolic segment in this equation to find,<n>```<n>a1+a2*cos(θ)+(a2-a​1)*sin(θ)=d<n>```<n><n>Then by plugging in the substitution of `x = a`, `y = -(x-a1)`, `z = c-a2`, we get the following,<n>```<n>-a1+a2+a2*cosθ+(a2-a​2)*sinθ=c-a2<n>```<n><n>Then we simplify the equation by cancelling θ by using,<n>```<n>-2*a1+a2-2*a2+a2=c-a2,<n>``` <n>which can be simplified to,<n>```<n>(1-2 )*a2-(a1+a2)=c-a2<n>or<n>-2*(1-2 )a2+a2-a1-=c-a2.<n>```<n>Since two variables are on the LHS, let's multiply by `x`. We have,<n>```<n>-10a2+1-x

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What does someone want when having fun with their friends and trying to fit in? Choices:  A: being understood B: beer C: playing around D: hug E: visiting friends<n><n>### Response:		Being understood, since the only choice out of the seven is B, being understood is the one you want. <n>### Rationales: Choice A: Being understood does not describe being understood to their friends, we need to pick the one choice that does say what someone wants when having fun with their friend and trying to fit in.<n>Choices B and C: These choices describe what you want when having fun with your friends, but it is not really a priority because you probably won't know who wants what.<n>Choices D and E: Hugging and visiting friends would not be fun, rather they are used to understand.<n><n><n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:He wore the wrong shoes while walking all day, now he has what on his heels and toes? The farmer is upset, he had been searching a long time and then he finds a cow that costs the same as the first cow he saw and the seller is asking for the high price!<n>The farmer has the $120 cow buy one last cow and then head to the market.<n>How much did the farmer pay to buy the cow that he bought last?<n><n>Solution:<n>Let's say that<n>a = <<$1600>>1600<n>b = <<$1300>>1300<n>c = <<$1200>>1200<n>d = <<$12>>12<n><n>Then,<n><n>a + b+c+d=1400 + 1300 +1200 +12=<<1400+1300+1200+12=2300>>2300.<n><n>The last cow's price is c+d=<<1200+c+12>>1200+<<12>>12=<<1201>>1201.<n>Then,<n><n>2300-1201=<<230

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. Choices:  A: look at B: write down C: learn new D: think about E: discovery of new<n><n>### Response:		Discovery of new<n><n>## Demonstrations<n>> ## 212-RN: Rational Functions<n>> #### Level of Difficulty<n>> Medium<n>> #### Outcomes<n>> - Students will be able to understand that rational functions are one to one relationships<n>> - Students should be able to graph rational functions.<n>> - Students can interpret the graphical behaviour of rational functions.<n>> #### Vocabulary<n>> - rational function - A function that can be written in the form $y = \frac{p(x)}{q(x)}$, where $p(x), q(x) $ are polynomials with no $x$ - co-efficients<n>> - Domain - the set of all possible $x$-values<n>> - Range - the set of all $y$-values obtainable from a function<n>> - zeros - values of $x$ for which $f(x) = 0$<n>> - inverse - the function that reverses the effect of another function<n>> - y -intercept - where the vertical line intersects the $y$-axis<n>> - asymptotes - lines that approach the graph of $y=f(x)$ but do not touch it, the vertical asymptote of $y=11x -7$ is -3$<3<7<11$<n>> - maximum/minimum and their rates of change - points where the rate of change of $f$ is $f$'s largest/smallest, respectively and where the graph of $f$ changes direction<n>> #### Questions<n>> #### In what situations are rational functions of use?<n>> They are functions that are used to describe things that have certain relationships with one another in different situations. When the relationship of one to another is constant, it is used. For example, the relationship between height and weight of a person and height and girth of a person<n>> #### What are the three properties of a rational function?<n>> Polynomial division property: any function can be written as $y = g(x)/h(x)$ with $g(x), h(x)$ nonzero polynomials. Then, the quotient $f(x)=g(x)/h( x)$ has the same domain as $g(x)$ but is larger, $f(x)$'s domain is $<x>$.<n>Polynomial division - property<n>Pol

Choices:  A: reverse B: backwards C: back and D: back and E: tally back<n><n>### Response:		A: reverse<n><n>### Rationales:The meaning behind "Go forth" is "proceed". "Reverse" mean "the action of returning".<n>The meaning behind "also this" is "what precedes this word, thing, or idea".<n>In "to go forth, also this", "also this" is reversing "this", meaning "to go forth".<n>"To go forth" can also reverse "forth", meaning proceed.<n>####<n><n>### Input and Context:Margot is a manager of the Sales and Service department at the Making Everything Easy Shoppe. Her co-worker, Betsy, is a manager of the Receiving Department.  According to Margot, "It takes ten minutes to unpack a box of merchandise and put it on the shelf. I can work this fast, even when I'm sick or I haven't had breakfast yet." Making Everything Easy's computer system automatically records the time that a box of merchandisewas unpacked. Margot thinks that if she could work 12 boxes a day, she could unpack each box faster than Betsy. "I can unpack 12 boxes if I work fast, and if I work 9 hours each day, it still takes only 3 minutes extra for each box. I can make up this tiny extra time by being efficient. That's why I'm working 12 boxes each day," she says. Betsy's unpacking time is 99 seconds per box. The Sales and Service Department's workday is 8 am to 4 pm. What will the time be, in minutes, when Margot finishes unpacking 128 boxes in a day?<n><n>### Rationale: According to Margot, the time to unpack a box is ten minutes if she works hard enough, even if she hadn't eaten yet.<n>If margot is working 12 boxes of merchandise each day, it would take her 20 x minutes to unpack and if she was working 9 hours per day, it would be 9 x minutes. That is 3 times as much time to unpack 128 boxes each day.<n>#### 20 x + 9 x<n><n>The answer is: 3minutes.

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:A shower is an expected amenity when you reserve a what? Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Lindy was a senior.  He lived with his children because he didn't want to go where? Choices:  A: republican party B: old people's home C: office D: park E: high school or college<n><n>### Response:		Lindy is not a senior. He should be living with his children because he went to the office, high school, to the park, or the republican party. He is not in the old people's home because he is not an old person. I suspect that he is a young person, and is not yet a senior.<n>

We did not give the building a lift nor did we make anything bigger. We did fix it and that can also raise a home because it allows the room to have more windows. Since the action is about destroying and not raising, the choice is not 'B'. 'C' is not correct because enticing has something to do with the building itself, we did not entice our new barn from a place, the action was to destroy our old barn and we don't entice anything because that would be 'E' the choice. Also the word "having time to think" is a noun.<n>

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Where would you get a bag after someone fills it with clothes? I see that shopping cart is a way to get a bag.<n>#### 23<n>Answer: B<n><n>### Input::<n>A: A student was paid $15 to put together a new set of encyclopedias and paid $11.50 to put together a new CD player.<n>B: A student was paid to install an air conditioner.<n>C: A student was paid for assembling stereos.<n>D: A student was paid by assembling a laptop.<n>E: A student was paid two hours to assemble chairs.<n>F: A student worked for two days to put together a car.<n><n>### Response:- A student was paid to put assemble a set of encyclopedies is choice A.<n>- A student was paid to assembly a CD player is choice B.<n>- A student working for assemble a stereo is choice C.<n>- A student worked to assembly a laptop is choice D.<n>- A student is paid to assemblechairs is choice E.<n>- A student works for two days to put assemble a car is choice F.<n>#### 44<n>Answer: A, B<n><n>### Instructions: Choose the best answer for each task.<n><n>### Input<n>How many days is it after a day before a day and a half?<n><n>### Response <n>1 day and half<n>#### 48<n>Answer: C<n><n>### Instuction: Fill in the blanks<n><n>### Input <n>The number of dogs times three plus the square of the number of cats minus the sum of the number of ducks, elephants, and lions is equal to 243. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Where do almost all people live? They even create different sections for new and used cars.<n><n>### Rationale: It seems to be a choice between car shows and houses based on the description. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Where do most people keep their curling iron stored? Choices:  A: bathroom B: walkway C: use D: hair salon E: drawer<n><n>### Response:		<n><n>### Dem:<n>Input: Where do most people keep their cookbooks? A: on a cookbook shelf B: on a kitchen counter C: on a bookshelf D: next to a stove E: next to a sink<n> Rationales: Choices for where most people keep their cook books. The possible places in order from most often found are: shelf, counter, bookshelf, next to stove (kitchen island), or next to sink (corner of kitchen).<n><n> Input: How do most people store their sunglasses? Choices: A: at the side of their bed B: in a cupboard C: on a shelf D: in a drawer E: in the bathroom **CORRECT:** F: in a bowl G: in a box H: in the kitchen J: at the desk K: in the kitchen<n><n>### Response<n>### Dem:

What is the average speed over 2n miles as compared to the total speed over 2n miiles?<n>Rationales:: The average speed over 2 n miles is 2 n miles * 50 mph = <<2n * 50 = 2n * 32>>2n * 352<n>The total speed over 2 n is 2n miles<n><n>#### 2n * 5 = n * 5<n><n>Answer: 400<n><n>### Input<n>An average of 7 million miles of roads are repaved each year. Last year 1953, 3600 miles that was repaved were destroyed due to weather. If a road were built for 10 million dollars and repaved for 300,000 dollars. How much did weather damage roads last year?<n><n>Rationales: There were 7 million -3600 = <<7 *(-3600)=3997>>3997 miles of paved roads and 7 million / 3997 = (answer) * 300/10 = $*3*200,00 / 10<n><n>#### $200<n><n>Answer: $300,0<n>### Input<n>  -8 less than 5 times a number<n>  = 11 more than 4 times the same number<n>  = 30 more than 9 times<n><n>Rationales:: (8) less than (5) times (a) : (8-5) less than (5 - 1) times (a)<n>Let 'a' = b, so that : (8 - 5) less than (b - 5) times (b)<n><n>::8 - 5 = 3, so that : (5 - 3) less than (3-1) times (a, the given number)<n><n>::2 less than 3 times a. so that : a + 2 less than 3 * (a)<n><n>::3 - (3a) is a, the given number<n>(answer = 
Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Danny was having fun singing in front of his class.   He has a lot of what? Choices:  A: laughter B: being happy C: glee D: opera E: injuries<n><n>### Response:		The correct response is E)Opera. What we are given is this "Danny was having fun sing-ing in front of his class". This is in the present tense.<n>We know that if it were not for the word present tense, the sentence would be grammatically incorrect.<n>It will be corrected if the word sings is changed into singing. This means that we have to change a singular form of a verb into a plural form to correct the error.<n>The present tense of the verb sing, according to the MLA handbook, is "sing."<n>The plural form of sing is "sings.<n>Thus, the correct response is E) opera.<n><n>#### Opera<n>Answer: E<n><n>### Input:-8, +19, -1, -5, +1, +1, +2<n><n>### Response:-5<n><n>### Input:(x-1)(x+6) What is the value of x? Choices: A: 1 B: 6 C: 100 D: 0 E: -7<n><n>### Response:(x-1)(1+6) = x^2 - 7x - 6 - x + 1 (x-1)(1-6) = 0<n>Since 1-6 = -5 and x-1 = x<n>We then simplify this further by taking x out of the equation. We have -5x + 1x - 6x + 5x - 6 = 0 - 1x - 5x + 6x = 0<n>(x-6)(x+1) = 0<n>(4/5)(-0)(0) = 0<n>x = 0<n><n>#### Answer:0<n><n>### Input:"One apple costs $1.75 and a loaf of sourdough bread costs 50 cents more." The cost of the 8-slice loaf of sourdread bread is how much?? Choices: A: $1.80 B: $2.00 C: $4.25<n><n>### Response:$2.00<n><n>###Input:A baseball team and basketball team were making a competition for charity. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:Changing society using a violent conflict is know as a what? Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What do humans take in while breathing? Choices: A: ablaze B: burning C: incinerate D: smoldering E: wild fire<n><n>### Response; A B C D E<n><n>## Summary<n><n>> In this exercise we demonstrated how to write an instruction that requested a specific response, and demonstrated how to write a response that appropriately completed the request. Choices:  A: were thirsty B: toasting C: getting drunk D: refreshment E: celebrating<n><n>### Response:		C<n><n>### Question:How would you compare a group of 14 with a group of 1?<n>### Answer: Increase <n><n><n>### Demystified Topics<n>#### Increase by 1<n><n>Increase by $15$<n><n>Increase from 1.1 to 1.2<n><n>### Demisterfied Topics<n><n>#### Addition<n><n>$10$ <n><n>$12$ <n><n>$+2$<n><n>${12}+{7}= 19$<n><n>#### Subtraction<n><n>$7$<n><n>$5$<n><n>$-2$<n><n>${-5}+{-2}=\infty$<n><n>#### Multiplication<n><n>$2$<n><n>$54$<n><n>${2}(54)= 108$<n><n>#### Division<n><n><n>#### Number of 1's in the Input<n><n>2<n><n>${+1}+{-1}=\infty$<n><n>2<n><n>$<n>\begin{align*}<n>+4  &= {1}+{-1}+{1}+{-1}= \infty\\<n>\end{align*}$<n><n>#### Division, Mod and Percentage<n><n>$47.6\%$ of $30$ <n><n>${47.6}\cdot{{30}\over{100}}={21}.$<n><n><n>### In the 7:48, is it greater than, greater than or equal to 9:14?<n>#### Greater than<n><n>```<n>8+14-9 >23+<9+4-3>30+23=53 <n><n>```<n><n>#### Greater than or equal to<n><n>```<n>8 =8+0, so greater than or equal to.<n>```<n><n>#### Equal to and less than<n><n>Equal to and less than means we will not be able to determine between.<n><n>```<n>8 is not equal to since 8 = 8 = 8, 14 is not equal to since =8=14, <n>9 is less then 14 because 8+1=12, so 12 is lesser then 14.<n>```<n><n>[Todo]: Add a picture how to choose one of two choices when we have more

How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:John is getting something important. Choices:  A: then have B: headaches C: stoic D: being happy E: wanting more<n><n>### Response:		D<n><n>### Demonsration:<n>Cross Multiplying we get:<n><n>3*6*4=<<3*6*4>><n><n>#### 144<n>Answer:D<n><n>## Input:Amy had to write an 8-foot by 16-foot rectangle in one day. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:He would finally see idea become reality, never in a million years did he what that this would happen? If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:What is a negative effect to someone other than a spouse when two spouses are getting divorced? Grief: a feeling of distress over an event experienced or imagined as an interference with well-being.<n>2. Lot: a large number or amount.<n>3. Grief: a person's sorrow and distress over the loss of someone or something.<n>Therefore A: the feeling of distress over a large number or amount of event experienced or imagined an interference with well being is a negative effect to the spouse who experience a divorce.<n>```<n><n>```<n>B: depression<n>1. Depression: a state of mental depression, typically characterized by feelings of sadness, lack of energy, and a general decrease in feelings of well-being. Feelings of sadness and decreased feelings of well-beng is a negative effect to a spouse that suffered from depression.<n><n>2. Depression: a  state of mental depression from which there is no apparent reason to recover that is characterized by feelings of hopelessness and often, in severe cases, suicidal thoughts<n>Therefore B: A loss of mental depression typically characterized by feelings and hopelessness is depression and  that is characterized by a lack of energy is sadness.<n><n>3. Depression: a chronic, frequently mild and recurrent form of depression, usually of short duration, usually with more positive and less intense symptoms than a major depression. These are negative effects to a spouse since there is a hopeless state <n><n>```<n>C: No spouse<n>1. No spouse: means that the spouses are no longer together and hence would not be together during the divorce process hence meaning that they are not with each other emotionally and this is a negative effect for the spouse.<n>```<n><n><n>```<n>D: lose money<n>1. Lose money: the act of losing money or being without money; loss, bankruptcy, ruin, poverty. To spend money on is a positive effect, not necessarily the actual result. Therefore loosing money is therefore a negative effect to a person.<n>2. Lose money: to be without money, to lack an amount of money specified or implied<n>3. Lose money: lose money, fail to attain an anticipated benefit, or sustain an expected loss

If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:James is very interested in other planets. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:James was looking for a place to buy bitcoins. Below is an instruction that describes a task. Write a response that appropriately completes the request.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>### Demonstration:<n>Input: Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90. If the number of Doberman puppies is 20, how many Schnauzers are there?<n>Rationales: Three times the number of Doberman puppies is 3*20=<<3*20=60>>60<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies is 60-5=<<60-5=55>>55<n>Let's say the number of Schnauzers is s.<n>The difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is s-20<n>Five less than three times the number of Doberman puppies plus the difference between the number of Doberman puppies and the number of Schnauzers is equal to 90, meaning 55+s-20=90.<n>The number of Schnauzers which is s+55-20=90<n>This evaluates to s+35=90<n>There are s=<<55=55>>55 Schnauzers<n>#### 55<n>Answer: 55<n><n>Input: Dr. Banks had 330 toothbrushes to give away to his patients. He gave away 53 toothbrushes in January. He gave away 67 toothbrushes in February. In March he gave away 46 toothbrushes. In April and May, he gave away the remaining toothbrushes, half each month.  How many more toothbrushes did Dr. Banks give out in the busiest month versus the slowest month?<n>Rationales: Through March, Dr. Banks gave out 53 + 67 + 46 = <<53+67+46=166>>166 toothbrushes.<n>Before giving away toothbrushes in April, he had 330 -166 = <<330-166=164>>164 toothbrushes remaining.<n>Between April and May, he gave out the remaining 164 / 2 = <<164/2=82>>82 toothbrushes each month.<n>Dr. Banks gave 82 toothbrushes in his busiest month and 46 toothbrushes during the slowest month.<n>The difference would be 82- 46 = <<82-46=36>>36 more toothbrushes in the busiest month.<n>#### 36<n>Answer: 36<n><n>### Input:After attending school for twelve years what do you do? Choices:  A: inspiration B: much work C: boredom D: graduate E: degree<n><n>### Response:		C<n><n><n>[Demonstration:](https://tympanus.net/Examples/HtmlTidyDifference/)<n><n>### Instructions<n>Write a program that takes a string and counts (or counts occurrences of) each character in the string, and writes it back to stdout formatted as a percentage out of (e.g.) 100% as in percentage.<n><n>### Input<n><n>![](/assets/img/2.PNG)<n><n>### Output<n><n>![](/assets.png)<n><n>### Answer<n><n>[![The answer is C][966e7815]]<n><n>### Notes<n><n>Examples:<n><n>	% gcc -o percentage percentage.c<n>	%./percence c<n><n>	% gcc  -o percentage percentage.cpp<n>	%./percentage  c<n><n>[966e770c]: https://github.com/Kyungyoon/Algorithm/blob/main/TASK/6/README.md#73-question-128<n>[966d2d3a]: https://github. com/Kyungyoo/Algorithm/blob<n>[966c4bbf]: https://github.co m/Kyungyuno/Algorithm/blob
